---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CTA from '../../components/CTA.astro';
---

<Base
  title="California EV Charger Rebates & Incentives in 2026"
  description="Save thousands on your EV charger installation with federal tax credits, state rebates, and local utility incentives available in California in 2026."
>
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-20 md:py-24">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-cover bg-center" style="background-image: url('/images/hero-circuit.webp')">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/60"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="relative max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold mb-4">California EV Charger Rebates & Incentives in 2026</h1>
      <p class="text-white/80 text-lg">Updated guide to federal, state, and local programs that reduce your installation cost</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <a href="/blog/" class="inline-flex items-center text-primary font-semibold mb-8 hover:underline">&larr; Back to Blog</a>
      <time class="block text-sm text-gray mb-6">March 21, 2026</time>

      <div class="space-y-6 text-gray leading-relaxed">
        <p class="text-lg text-dark font-medium">
          Installing a home EV charger in California is more affordable than ever thanks to a combination of federal tax credits, state rebates, and utility-specific incentive programs. Bay Area homeowners can save $2,000 to $4,000 or more when they stack available programs correctly. Here is a comprehensive breakdown of every incentive available in 2026.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Federal 30C Tax Credit: Up to $1,000 Back</h2>
        <p>
          The Alternative Fuel Vehicle Refueling Property Credit (Section 30C of the Internal Revenue Code) remains one of the most straightforward incentives for homeowners. In 2026, this credit covers 30% of the total cost of purchasing and installing an EV charger, up to a maximum of $1,000 for residential installations.
        </p>
        <p>
          The credit applies to both the equipment cost and labor. For example, if your total EV charger installation costs $2,500 (including the charger unit and professional installation), you would receive $750 back on your federal tax return. If your total exceeds $3,334, you hit the $1,000 cap.
        </p>
        <p>
          Important details: This is a tax credit, not a deduction, meaning it directly reduces your tax liability dollar for dollar. You claim it using IRS Form 8911 when filing your annual return. The property must be located in an eligible census tract — most Bay Area locations qualify.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">California CALeVIP (California Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Project)</h2>
        <p>
          CALeVIP provides rebates for EV charger installations across California, though availability varies by county and funding cycles. The program is administered by the California Energy Commission and offers rebates ranging from $500 to $2,500 for residential Level 2 chargers, depending on your location and income qualification.
        </p>
        <p>
          For Bay Area residents, the program has historically offered between $1,000 and $1,500 for standard residential installations. Income-qualified applicants (those earning below 80% of Area Median Income) may receive enhanced rebates of up to $2,500. Check the CALeVIP website for current funding availability in your specific county, as allocations can be exhausted quickly.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">PG&E EV Charge Network Programs</h2>
        <p>
          Pacific Gas & Electric offers several programs for Bay Area EV owners. The most relevant for homeowners is the EV Rate Plan (EV-2A), which provides significantly reduced electricity rates during off-peak hours — typically between 12:00 AM and 3:00 PM. While this is not a direct installation rebate, switching to an EV rate can save you $50 to $100 per month on charging costs.
        </p>
        <p>
          PG&E also periodically offers rebates of $500 to $800 for purchasing and installing a qualifying Level 2 charger. These programs come and go based on regulatory approvals, so check PG&E's current offerings or ask us during your consultation — we stay current on all active utility programs.
        </p>
        <p>
          For multi-family properties, PG&E's EV Fleet program provides infrastructure support including panel upgrades and conduit installation at no cost to the property owner, with the utility retaining ownership of the infrastructure.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Bay Area Air Quality Management District (BAAQMD) Programs</h2>
        <p>
          BAAQMD offers grants through its Clean Cars for All program that can cover EV charger installation costs for income-qualifying residents. If you are replacing a gasoline vehicle with an EV, you may be eligible for up to $5,000 in combined vehicle replacement and charger installation incentives. This program targets households in disadvantaged communities or those with incomes below 400% of the federal poverty level.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">TECH Clean California</h2>
        <p>
          While primarily focused on building decarbonization, the TECH Clean California program occasionally includes EV-ready electrical panel upgrades in its incentive structure. If you need a panel upgrade to support your EV charger (a common requirement in older Bay Area homes), this program may offset $1,000 to $2,000 of that cost. Panel upgrades from Fox EV Install start at $2,800, so this can meaningfully reduce your out-of-pocket expense.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">How to Stack Incentives for Maximum Savings</h2>
        <p>
          The key to maximizing your savings is stacking multiple programs. Most of these incentives can be combined. Here is a realistic example for a Bay Area homeowner:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>EV charger installation from Fox EV Install: $799 (standard installation with dedicated circuit)</li>
          <li>Charger unit (e.g., ChargePoint Home Flex): $600</li>
          <li>Total project cost: $1,399</li>
          <li>Federal 30C credit (30%): -$420</li>
          <li>CALeVIP rebate: -$1,000</li>
          <li>Net cost after incentives: as low as $0 (depending on program availability)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Even without CALeVIP funding, the federal credit alone brings your effective installation cost down significantly. If you also need a panel upgrade (from $2,800) or a dedicated circuit (from $499), additional programs like TECH Clean California can further reduce expenses.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Tips for Claiming Your Incentives</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Apply for rebate programs before installation when possible — some require pre-approval</li>
          <li>Keep all receipts, invoices, and permit documentation</li>
          <li>Take before and after photos of your electrical panel and installation</li>
          <li>File Form 8911 with your tax return for the federal credit</li>
          <li>Work with a licensed C-10 contractor (required for most programs) — Fox EV Install meets all licensing requirements</li>
          <li>Check income qualification for enhanced rebates even if you think you might not qualify — thresholds are higher than many expect in the Bay Area</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Act Before Funding Runs Out</h2>
        <p>
          State and local rebate programs operate on a first-come, first-served basis. CALeVIP allocations in the Bay Area have historically been exhausted within months of becoming available. The federal 30C credit is stable through at least 2032, but state programs face annual budget constraints.
        </p>
        <p>
          Contact Fox EV Install for a free consultation and we will help you identify every incentive you qualify for, handle the paperwork, and ensure your installation meets all program requirements. Our standard EV charger installation starts at $799, and with available incentives, your net cost could be significantly lower.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTA title="Get Your EV Charger Installed and Save with Rebates" subtitle="We help you navigate every incentive program available" />
</Base>
